Using software decomposition (SymPhoTime), we found that the luminescence can be well fitted with a tri-exponential function (Fig. 7
                     , Table 2
                     ). Table 2 presents the data on the intensity ratios and the luminescence decay time constants for the samples CD, rCD1, rCD2, rCD3, rCD4. The average values of the luminescence decay time components for the samples CD, rCD1, rCD2, rCD3 can be expressed as follows: fast component τ1 ∼ 0.53 ns, intermediate component τ2 ∼ 2.4 ns and slow component τ3 ∼ 7.45 ns. The contribution of photons to each luminescence component can be described in the following percentage ratio A1 ∼ 50.88 %, A2 ∼ 40.87 %, A3 ∼ 8.25 %. At NaBH4 concentration below 2.5 mg/mL in the samples, no significant changes in the luminescence decay time constants of CDs are observed. However, at a NaBH4 concentration of 25 mg/mL (rCD4), an increase in the decay time constants is observed (τ1 ∼ 0.68 ns, τ2 ∼ 2.7 ns and τ3 ∼ 8.23 ns). It should also be noted that for the rCD4 sample with a high concentration of NaBH4, a change in the intensity of the time components in percentage is observed. While the average photon contribution to each luminescence component of CDs is described by the following percentages: A1 ∼ 50.88 %, A2 ∼ 40.87 %, A3 ∼ 8.25 %, for the rCD4 sample, the values are A1 ∼ 43.69 %, A2 ∼ 44.78 %, A3 ∼ 11.53 %. If the NaBH4 concentration is increased to 50 mg/mL, the ratio will be as follows: A1 ∼ 33.77 %, A2 ∼ 52.97 %, A3 ∼ 13.26 %. The addition of sodium borohydride to the CDs solution leads to a selective decrease in the intensity contribution A1 of the fast luminescence component (τ1), as well as to a slight increase in the intensity contributions for the intermediate (τ2) and slow (τ3) components. It follows that the fast luminescence component (τ1) refers to the carbonyl functional group (C=O) on the CDs surface. It can then be assumed that the intermediate and slow components are associated with the hydroxyl group (OH), but this statement remains debatable at this stage. Thus, identification of the luminescence center and its connection to the fast luminescence decay component has been carried out. This result is important for understanding the luminescence mechanism of CDs and for developing methods to control it.
